<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-721-714  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 721 714.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Oct 1989 v14 n10 p231(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computing with light. (optical computers)(includes relatedarticles on optical processors and holography)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Caulfield, H. John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Optical technology today is poorly developed and costly as well asunreliable and unstandardized, but can perform important tasksthat electronic circuits cannot and can work together withelectronics in hybrid systems.andP;  Optics can provide large numbersof input and output connections to a processor without the wiresand bonding pads electronics require.andP;  They can also operate at anaverage energy per calculation lower than the theoretical minimumfor an electronic logic gate.andP;  The SLM, a discrete or continuousarray of light modulator whose reflection or transmissionproperties can be controlled, is the key component of an opticalcomputer.andP;  Optics are well suited for connections and storage butnot for computation because the accuracy rate is low.andP;  Researchfocuses on computers that combine optical processors forcomputationally complex tasks with higher-accuracy digital parts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optoelectronic devicesOptical MemoryComputer DesignMassive ParallelismFuture Technologies.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Generic optical computer. (chart)Representative optical processing functions. (chart)Optical multiplier. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>